Next is Jerry Bostic. Jerry holds a degree in civil engineering.

03:15.000 --> 03:23.000
He joined NASA as an aerospace engineer at the Langley Space Center in 1962 and he transferred to Houston in the same year.

03:23.000 --> 03:28.000
He worked as a flight controller for the Mercury, Gemini, Apollo, and Skylab missions.

03:28.000 --> 03:32.000
He was the flight dynamics officer for the Apollo 13 mission.

03:32.000 --> 03:42.000
His other positions at NASA included executive assistant to the NASA administrator, deputy manager of the Space Shuttle program, and director of mission support.

03:42.000 --> 03:52.000
Since leaving NASA, he has worked as the vice president of space systems for grumman corporation and he is currently the director of business development for Northrop Grumman Technical Services.

03:52.000 --> 04:02.000
And on my far right is John Aaron. John holds a degree in physics.

04:02.000 --> 04:08.000
He joined NASA in 1964 as a vehicle systems engineer for the Gemini program.

04:08.000 --> 04:12.000
John was a flight controller for the Gemini and Apollo missions.

04:12.000 --> 04:19.000
During the Skylab program, he was a section head for electrical power, sequential and instrumentation systems.

04:19.000 --> 04:34.000
His other positions at NASA have included management positions working with spacecraft software, management positions with the space station program, acting assistant administrator for exploration, and assistant director of engineering at the Johnson Space Center.

04:34.000 --> 04:38.000
He is currently the manager of the Systems Engineering Office. Let's welcome all of them.

04:38.000 --> 04:45.000
Thank you.

04:45.000 --> 04:53.000
Okay, this is going to be a very informal session up here. We haven't rehearsed this script.

04:53.000 --> 05:01.000
The Apollo 13, I think, was really had several key points associated with.

05:01.000 --> 05:10.000
The first thing was, I look at it as a real miracle of leadership. We were fortunate all of us up here to grow up under some exemplary leaders.

05:10.000 --> 05:19.000
We had George Miller. We had Jim McDevitt, George Lowe. We had Chris Kraft, Deeks Layton, Dr. Gilruth.

05:19.000 --> 05:26.000
Each of these people gave true meaning to authority with responsibility.

05:26.000 --> 05:34.000
So that when it came time to fly missions, these folks were with us every step of the way. They gave us the job and they expected us to do it.

05:34.000 --> 05:41.000
I think that was one of the real keys to the success of that mission and all the missions that we had in the program.

05:41.000 --> 05:46.000
The second element was associated with the people. The people were universally young.

05:46.000 --> 05:56.000
They were convinced that the impossible was truly possible. They had gone through very rigorous training. They had grown up in the business of mission operations.

05:56.000 --> 06:10.000
And we would spend the days, weeks, months, and eventually the years together, not only working in mission control but working in our offices, building the game plan, developing confidence in ourselves and confidence in each other.

06:10.000 --> 06:18.000
The training personnel we had were the best in the world because those were the ones that gave us the can-do attitude, the never surrender.

06:18.000 --> 06:24.000
And with that kind of a background, we moved into the Apollo program.

06:24.000 --> 06:30.000
There had been several very key missions in Apollo and everyone up here worked those missions.

06:30.000 --> 06:36.000
We went to the moon in Apollo 11. We had difficulties getting down to the surface but we made it.

06:36.000 --> 06:47.000
Apollo 12, where you were struck by lightning and I believe Jerry was the flight director there and you've got another key guy in his right-hand air and you made the calls to get the spacecraft back to life again.

06:47.000 --> 06:51.000
Apollo 13 came along so we were no...

06:51.000 --> 06:57.000
The kinds of problems that we had, we were convinced we could work in the lake.

06:57.000 --> 07:02.000
So I think we were ready at 55-55 when the problem occurred on board the spacecraft.

07:02.000 --> 07:07.000
Everything had been normal up to that time. We had gone through two team rotations. We had four teams going.

07:07.000 --> 07:16.000
We had Milton Lur, the marine flight director who launched the mission I believe Jerry did, actually did the transposition in docking.

07:16.000 --> 07:21.000
I had the lunar orbit insertion. I was going to do the lunar acid.

07:21.000 --> 07:33.000
Glenn Loney was really the guy who was making sure that us rookies in the non-trijectory business did our work properly and by the book.

07:33.000 --> 07:39.000
So we had gone through the two team's successions and everything was optional up to that point. Jerry, why don't you say it?

07:39.000 --> 07:44.000
I'd like to pick up on a couple of... in Amplify a couple of James Remarks.

07:44.000 --> 07:50.000
I think at the time...well I know at the time in my own case in Apollo 13 I was 35.

07:50.000 --> 07:58.000
I probably had more responsibility at age 34, 35, 36 and I've ever had before or since.

07:58.000 --> 08:05.000
And as Jean said, this was really important in Apollo 13 because when we did get into trouble,

08:06.000 --> 08:15.000
the senior management of the agency and the senior management of this center really only had one question of us on the flight control team.

08:15.000 --> 08:20.000
What can we do to help you? They really did leave the decision making to a bunch of young people.

08:20.000 --> 08:27.000
I think Jean was probably 37 and he was probably the oldest flight director on that flight.

08:27.000 --> 08:34.000
I think John Aaron was 27 or something like that. Jerry was 28.

08:34.000 --> 08:38.000
No, you weren't.

08:38.000 --> 08:51.000
Anyway, it was a young person's game and then sometime when I reflect and we'll obviously in this session we'll get into more of the problem and how we fixed it and that sort of thing.

08:51.000 --> 08:56.000
One of the things I thought about after the flight was over and this didn't occur to me during the mission,

08:56.000 --> 09:03.000
as soon as we landed every one of these lunar missions we didn't have much time to dwell on it. We had to go on to the next one.

09:03.000 --> 09:09.000
Well that was no exception in this case. The only difference is we had this big problem.

09:09.000 --> 09:15.000
And the amazing thing to me is that after we landed this was in April 1970.

09:15.000 --> 09:24.000
We had a complete accident investigation. We had a set of congressional hearings.

09:24.000 --> 09:31.000
We had to go fix the problem, redo the command module pretty extensively in the oxygen system.

09:31.000 --> 09:38.000
And we went back to the moon in less than a year. In fact we were there in about 10 months later we flew Apollo 14.

09:38.000 --> 09:54.000
Now that shows you another difference in attitude that existed 25 years ago is when you had a problem and you had this adversity to overcome rather than wailing and gnashing of teeth and worrying about the future.

09:54.000 --> 10:01.000
You set the problem right and charged on because you had not changed your initial goals.

10:01.000 --> 10:11.000
And I think that was very fortunate time with today's oversight and other kinds of problems that you get into.

10:11.000 --> 10:18.000
It would be extremely difficult to do what we did in 1970-71 to get the program back on track.

10:18.000 --> 10:28.000
So I think it's a very interesting historical perspective and it's one we probably ought to keep in mind for the future.

10:28.000 --> 10:36.000
Finally, and I'm not going to say too much about it. I think Jerry Bostic ought to say something about the Apollo they've asked us to talk a little bit about the Apollo 13 movie.

10:36.000 --> 10:44.000
It was a great experience. Jerry and I got to work on it as technical advisors and is an interesting way that project got started.

10:44.000 --> 10:52.000
But maybe Jerry will fill you in on that. And I really do think it's brought alive a lot of interest in the American public.

10:52.000 --> 11:02.000
It's taken us back 25 years and it's brought up some of these successes and overcoming of failures that I think is a very positive thing and it's good for the space program.

11:02.000 --> 11:10.000
Jerry.

11:10.000 --> 11:16.000
I had forgotten how much older you guys were.

11:16.000 --> 11:27.000
The movie has brought a lot of attention back to the mission and it has caused all of us to reflect a lot on what happened 25 years ago.

11:27.000 --> 11:33.000
And it was kind of strange to me at first that almost everyone asked the same question.

11:33.000 --> 11:36.000
Aren't you guys scared to death when the accident happened?

11:36.000 --> 11:42.000
Aren't you running around ringing your hands and pulling your hair out?

11:42.000 --> 11:48.000
And of course the answer was no. And in the next question is why.

11:48.000 --> 11:54.000
Well, the only reason I can think why is because of the training that we had had which was.

11:54.000 --> 12:04.000
I don't think we fully understood it at the time, but it's a good training for any endeavor that you undertake and that is to try to anticipate the problems that are going to happen.

12:04.000 --> 12:12.000
I have a plan of action for anything that you can dream of that will possibly come up.

12:12.000 --> 12:18.000
But in reality after the accident occurred.

12:18.000 --> 12:29.000
And for the next four days while we tried to figure out collectively how to get the crew home, we didn't have a lot of time to.

12:29.000 --> 12:35.000
To worry about anything except the task at hand and there was a time to ring your hands and pull their hair.

12:35.000 --> 12:49.000
It was a great example of teamwork over the past 10 years or so anyway in the in the aerospace industry.

12:49.000 --> 12:55.000
There's been a lot of attention on total quality management and.

12:55.000 --> 12:58.000
Things like that and it.

12:58.000 --> 13:09.000
It occurred to me not too long ago that even though we didn't know it at the time, that's what we were all practicing here at Johnson Space Center 25 and 30 years ago.

13:09.000 --> 13:19.000
It was a true team work. Everybody knew the task that they had to do and we tried to do it the best that we could.

13:19.000 --> 13:27.000
Thank you.

13:27.000 --> 13:33.000
Maybe I could present a little bit of what my role was this mission and give you my impressions of what was accomplished.

13:33.000 --> 13:38.000
I was a systems engineer. I'm manned one of the the controller consoles and mission control center.

13:38.000 --> 13:48.000
My job was since there was two space ships involved going to the moon, one to be the mothership to transport the landing craft the moon called the lunar module.

13:48.000 --> 13:56.000
I was in charge of all the subsystems, all the vital systems and utilities to keep the both the mothership alive and sustained the crew.

13:56.000 --> 13:59.000
So I had a very important responsibility.

13:59.000 --> 14:06.000
My role in the mission was initially to be on the launch phase team as Jean mentioned and that would have rotate me and be in the landing phase.

14:06.000 --> 14:16.000
I wound up being on the part of the team that was charged with the awful decision of trying to decide whether or not to shut the mothership down as a result of this explosion.

14:16.000 --> 14:25.000
How much longer should we spend our precious power versus diagnosis in the system versus the decision to shut it down and depends truly on the lifeboat.

14:25.000 --> 14:36.000
Having been a part of that decision process, we then, while the lifeboat team tried to understand how to get the mothership back in the vicinity of the earth safely,

14:36.000 --> 14:43.000
I was charged with the awful responsibility of leading the team that says given that these guys, the lifeboat team can get us back in the vicinity of the earth,

14:43.000 --> 14:48.000
is there any way to turn this thing back on given this limited power that we've got.

14:49.000 --> 14:57.000
The reason I bring you through that sequence is not only a quaint you with my responsibility was, but I think the thing that I most well fit that mission is,

14:57.000 --> 15:02.000
as I sum it up to people, my conclusion is it works.

15:02.000 --> 15:10.000
Now, what I mean by that is, in any complex endeavor like going to the moon, of which stuff is a very complex endeavor,

15:10.000 --> 15:18.000
and we on the ground here as part of the design team, we did design, design, design, and we did train, train, train, and what if planning,

15:18.000 --> 15:22.000
we tried to cover every contingency we trained day and night.

15:22.000 --> 15:26.000
I think what this mission serves as, it's a model of that.

15:26.000 --> 15:32.000
There is a method by which, you know, I only can train and design for all the cases you think will happen to you,

15:32.000 --> 15:42.000
but that very method and model and training process will help you react in a very successful way to things you never envisioned and never thought you could handle.

15:42.000 --> 15:46.000
We wound up with a situation that we never trained for.

15:46.000 --> 15:53.000
The spacecraft, the mission was certainly never designed for, but those fundamental methods in this management team and this process,

15:53.000 --> 15:56.000
are served to be the thing that got us home.

15:56.000 --> 16:06.000
I think that's a model for our future that says complex endeavors, there is a method to handle the things you don't really train for, but the things you don't.

16:06.000 --> 16:12.000
As usual, John is being extremely modest about his role in the mission.

16:12.000 --> 16:24.000
He had it a team, actually, that had to try to figure out, indeed, how, that we could get the spacecraft back with the consumables that we had on board.

16:24.000 --> 16:30.000
We didn't have enough water, we didn't have enough electricity, we didn't have enough oxygen.

16:30.000 --> 16:48.000
And being a guy who worried about how to get to the people home from an Inflight trajectory standpoint, if I wanted to burn the engine or turn the platform on or anything to use the guidance system,

16:48.000 --> 16:54.000
I was going to go to John to try to convince him that I needed five hours of...

16:54.000 --> 17:00.000
One hour, one hour, one hour, ten minutes.

17:00.000 --> 17:06.000
Actually, at the time, we were at 55 hours into the mission.

17:06.000 --> 17:09.000
We were at our second rotation of the flight control team.

17:09.000 --> 17:12.000
It takes a while to get into the groove.

17:12.000 --> 17:22.000
We always looked towards that trans lunar phase as sort of a way to come up to speed in all of our homework, doing the final tag-ups with the various flight controllers we got.

17:22.000 --> 17:29.000
And just get ourselves ready for the events that would occur once we went into lunar orbit.

17:29.000 --> 17:41.000
We had finished the TV show, secured the downlink, and one of the things the flight controllers always pride themselves in is getting the crew to sleep on time and not having to wake them up during the sleep period.

17:42.000 --> 17:49.000
We were in the process of doing this when we asked the crew to go through a cryo-ster.

17:49.000 --> 17:53.000
And we did this because the cryogen extended to stratify in the tank.

17:53.000 --> 18:04.000
And we always liked to get our best measurement gauging on the cryo-tankage during the crew sleep period because we knew pretty much what their metabolic use was.

18:04.000 --> 18:07.000
So we could get a good handle on our consumables.

18:08.000 --> 18:15.000
So we told the crew to stir the cries, and Jack Swagger reached over, and he flipped four switches.

18:18.000 --> 18:24.000
Down in the ground, within just the next three seconds, three controllers reported the problem.

18:25.000 --> 18:29.000
And there was the guidance officer who identified that we had a hardware restart.

18:29.000 --> 18:37.000
Enco came in and said, Enco is the communications officer that we had switched from narrow to wide beam.

18:37.000 --> 18:45.000
And simultaneously, with that, we got a call from the ECOMS position that we had a main B undervolt.

18:45.000 --> 18:53.000
And about that time, hey, excuse me, Jack Swagger first, and then the level second came down and said, Houston, we got a problem.

18:53.000 --> 18:58.000
And it was funny how your mind works because the first thing I thought, which ones are you talking about?

18:58.000 --> 19:03.000
Are you talking about the hardware restart? The main B undervolt or the communications problem?

19:03.000 --> 19:06.000
And that wiped clear in just a second.

19:06.000 --> 19:14.000
And then you started listening up to the loops and all the controllers started to come on loops because virtually everybody in the control center had some,

19:14.000 --> 19:17.000
we're seeing some symptoms of the problems that occurred.

19:17.000 --> 19:22.000
And it was really confusing for those first two to three to four minutes because the reports kept coming in.

19:22.000 --> 19:24.000
Nothing made sense.

19:24.000 --> 19:27.000
The crew was changing the configuration on board to spacecraft.

19:27.000 --> 19:31.000
So about the time we'd get ready to make some recommendation to them.

19:31.000 --> 19:35.000
That recommendation would change because it changed something else.

19:35.000 --> 19:46.000
The GNNC or the guidance and control guy was worried because he was seeing a lot of pressure decay on the

19:46.000 --> 19:50.000
quads, the RCS jets that we used for attitude control.

19:50.000 --> 19:53.000
And this is because we didn't know it was at that time an explosion.

19:53.000 --> 19:57.000
But a shock had gone through the spacecraft that closed a lot of the valves.

19:57.000 --> 20:03.000
Actually, we were just bringing the propellant and the manifold to the jets and the manifold pressures were decaying.

20:03.000 --> 20:08.000
The spacecraft was in capable of being controlled. It was very difficult three or four minutes.

20:08.000 --> 20:15.000
But then after about three to three and a half minutes, the basic discipline and the training of the team and the quality of the spacecraft

20:15.000 --> 20:26.000
that the controllers started to take over in particular, the control guy recognized that the jets had been the valves had been closed.

20:26.000 --> 20:28.000
And that's why we couldn't control attitudes.

20:28.000 --> 20:31.000
So we now started solving our attitude problem.

20:31.000 --> 20:39.000
The communications guy came up and said, hey, until we get our attitude problem nailed down, let's use the omnithenic.

20:39.000 --> 20:43.000
So now we were getting information constantly into the spacecraft.

20:43.000 --> 20:48.000
The guidance officer, by this time very quickly, had come up and said he had the time of the hardware restart.

20:48.000 --> 20:54.000
So now we could start tracing back in our data at the possible time this occurred.

20:54.000 --> 21:02.000
So the control team over the next 10 to 15 minutes continued to work their problems with one exception.

21:02.000 --> 21:11.000
And that was the ECOM, Cyliburga, who had the consistent problems associated with the fuel cells and the cryogenics.

21:11.000 --> 21:16.000
And it became obvious. We were tracing, we were chasing instrumentation problems early.

21:16.000 --> 21:23.000
But by the time we were about 10 to 15 minutes into this episode, it became obvious that we were seeing some real problems.

21:23.000 --> 21:28.000
But we are still dubious about what information we could truly believe.

21:28.000 --> 21:38.000
But the crew, the controllers, the entire team was coming to the conclusion that we had problems in fuel cells, problems in cries, and it looked like at least two fuel cells were done.

21:38.000 --> 21:44.000
And about this time, about 15 minutes into this entire episode.

21:44.000 --> 21:56.000
We were in the process of changing shift, Lennon, it come in, and turned the gland and told him to get a hold of Chris that he better get in because we're in deep, serious trouble.

21:56.000 --> 22:06.000
And it was just frustrating to see the lifeblood in these fuel cells and cryo-escaping and not being able to do anything about it.

22:06.000 --> 22:10.000
And then Jim Lovell came down and said we're vetting something.

22:10.000 --> 22:15.000
And as soon as he said venting, that then sinked, I think, everybody in the team.

22:15.000 --> 22:21.000
I think everybody is sort of sent a chill down your spine that says, my God, we had some type of an explosion.

22:22.000 --> 22:24.000
And in my mind, the first thought I had was survival.

22:24.000 --> 22:27.000
That we're now in a survival situation.

22:27.000 --> 22:34.000
And these guys up here, it's somewhere along the line in their careers flight controllers, have looked at this thing we call the Doomsday scenario.

22:34.000 --> 22:39.000
And you look at straight in the face, and it's sort of gets your attention.

22:39.000 --> 22:40.000
Let me go ahead.

22:40.000 --> 22:49.000
Interestingly enough, because Jean and I talked about this, when the accident first happened, our thought was, now what do we got to do to go ahead with this landing mission?

22:50.000 --> 22:57.000
And then, and you got to know you got to that survival mode in a couple of steps, because that was the way we were trained.

22:57.000 --> 23:01.000
When it happens, what do we have to do now to make sure we can still land okay?

23:01.000 --> 23:03.000
And Jim Lovell was thinking the same way.

23:03.000 --> 23:07.000
He said, you know, we've had some kind of problem, but we'll get this fixed and go on and land on the moon.

23:07.000 --> 23:13.000
So it was interesting how you kind of step down, and all of a sudden you say there's no more options left.

23:14.000 --> 23:19.000
Now the game is to get them back, and forget the mission of going to the moon.

23:19.000 --> 23:23.000
We never trained to this Doomsday scenario, because it's non-beneficial.

23:23.000 --> 23:27.000
I mean, you end up killing the crew and the controllers, and up going home.

23:27.000 --> 23:28.000
So you never trained to this.

23:28.000 --> 23:33.000
So all of the training that we have, there's always some way out.

23:33.000 --> 23:35.000
And that's a way we're trained.

23:35.000 --> 23:38.000
And it went through my mind, in fact, in the voice loops.

23:39.000 --> 23:41.000
Let's not do anything that's going to blow the mission.

23:41.000 --> 23:46.000
Well, I was still thinking, well, if we can't land in the moon, we're going to go into orbit around the moon kind of thing.

23:46.000 --> 23:53.000
So it's the training process, it's interesting how your mind downloads under this kind of situation.

23:53.000 --> 23:57.000
We continued to work on this thing for the best part of another hour.

23:57.000 --> 24:01.000
We recognized very quickly, and we had two things going for us.

24:01.000 --> 24:06.000
In Apollo 9 mission, we had built something we call the lifeboat procedures.

24:07.000 --> 24:15.000
And about 45 minutes into this crisis, we went and proceeded to start digging out these lifeboat procedures.

24:15.000 --> 24:17.000
Because once you do something like that, you always save it.

24:17.000 --> 24:27.000
The other thing that was useful on this mission was we had done a lot of maneuvers using the LEM spacecraft during Apollo 9.

24:27.000 --> 24:29.000
And all that data was in archives.

24:29.000 --> 24:31.000
So we really started going two directions.

24:31.000 --> 24:38.000
We had to get the data out of archives from the Apollo 9 mission and the rest of controllers to dig out their lifeboat procedures.

24:38.000 --> 24:40.000
So I think that's all that these guys continue for a while.

24:40.000 --> 24:41.000
Yeah.

24:41.000 --> 24:43.000
Interesting.

24:43.000 --> 24:52.000
And I just don't know what made me think of this, but it'll show you a little bit how, by the time we got to Apollo 13, how we were thinking about going to the moon.

24:52.000 --> 24:54.000
This was our third landing mission.

24:54.000 --> 25:00.000
We had been there twice before on 10 and 8 and did not Apollo 10 and Apollo 8 and did not land.

