Thank you.

55:18.000 --> 55:39.000
Well, my question is, well, before the crew jettisoned the service module, you had no idea of the extent of the explosion.

55:39.000 --> 55:46.000
And of course, after it was jettisoned, the crew took a picture of it as it was floating away towards the atmosphere.

55:46.000 --> 55:53.000
What was going through your mind whenever you saw those pictures for the first time seeing how massive the explosion was?

55:53.000 --> 55:56.000
I think this is a good question for everybody.

55:56.000 --> 56:05.000
For my mind, because we had had a very intense debate in the control center, it was relatively short, whether to use the service propulsion engine.

56:05.000 --> 56:11.000
And Sarlovis lined up, I lined up and said, hey, we don't want to use it because we don't know what happened back there.

56:11.000 --> 56:15.000
The first thing that went through my mind was, thank God, we didn't use it.

56:15.000 --> 56:16.000
We tried to do that.

56:16.000 --> 56:17.000
Yeah, that's first thing.

56:17.000 --> 56:24.000
And of course, remember, we didn't see that picture immediately because we had to get the camera, but we didn't have TV on it.

56:24.000 --> 56:29.000
The crew took the picture, but they described it.

56:29.000 --> 56:34.000
And Jim said the whole panel on the side of that thing is blown out.

56:34.000 --> 56:42.000
The word picture, I had the same reaction that Jean did is, I had two thoughts.

56:42.000 --> 56:45.000
One was, thank God we didn't use the service engine, service propulsion system.

56:45.000 --> 56:54.000
But the second thing was, I wonder what's going to happen to that heat shield because the heat shield was the next question, just from his word description.

56:54.000 --> 56:55.000
It was frightening.

56:55.000 --> 57:01.000
My main thought was, I'm glad we didn't see it earlier because we didn't have that in the world.

57:02.000 --> 57:04.000
I'm really worried a lot more.

57:10.000 --> 57:13.000
How long did the actual explosion last?

57:13.000 --> 57:15.000
16 seconds.

57:17.000 --> 57:20.000
From the time they flipped the switches until the panel was gone.

57:22.000 --> 57:24.000
This is kind of a two part question.

57:24.000 --> 57:28.000
I'd like to find out what each of you, briefly, what each of you is doing now.

57:29.000 --> 57:40.000
And in second, is there any way that you feel that your knowledge and expertise and that of others like you could be more fully utilized now and in the future?

57:44.000 --> 57:49.000
I'll tell you what, we'll go this way here saying, what are we doing now and then they'll start that way.

57:49.000 --> 57:51.000
What can we do in the future?

57:52.000 --> 58:00.000
What I'm doing right now is I literally did retire. I'm building an aerobatic by plane. It's essentially complete.

58:00.000 --> 58:12.000
I got final painting to do a hope to be flying at this December. I also have been doing air shows throughout the last two summers and a flight engineering position to be 17 with the Lunnstern.

58:13.000 --> 58:22.000
I took early retirement from NASA in 1986 and went on the last ten years I've been involved in the private sector and a number of different businesses.

58:22.000 --> 58:28.000
And I'm currently living up in the hill country up near Curville in the little town of Hunt.

58:28.000 --> 58:31.000
If any of you know where that is, we're all the camps are.

58:31.000 --> 58:37.000
But I'm still a consultant. I chair the board of a public company that is based in California.

58:38.000 --> 58:42.000
And I'm still in the executive search business, but please no resumes today.

58:44.000 --> 58:49.000
I'm still in the aerospace business working for Grumman, a contractor here at JSC.

58:49.000 --> 58:55.000
And I hope to continue to be in the space business the rest of my life.

58:55.000 --> 58:58.000
The second part of the question.

58:58.000 --> 59:06.000
I might to come in on that. If you go over to the new control center here now and see what I call young kids operating over here.

59:08.000 --> 59:13.000
What they do, I feel real inadequate with what we did back in the old days.

59:13.000 --> 59:16.000
They have some real sharp people over there. They know what they're doing.

59:16.000 --> 59:22.000
And from a mission control standpoint, today NASA is in good hands.

59:24.000 --> 59:32.000
I'm still at NASA. I head up assistant engineering office where I still do engineering management and try to be mentors to young engineers coming up.

59:33.000 --> 59:37.000
I'm still a youngster at 52. So I've got a lot of time here at the Johnson Space Center.

59:37.000 --> 59:42.000
I hope to serve that role to bring up the new programs that we are working on.

59:42.000 --> 59:47.000
Space Station Space Shuttle, me on as well as be mentors to new engineers.

59:47.000 --> 59:51.000
I'd like to take a shot at that second question too.

59:51.000 --> 59:53.000
In Jerry hit part of it.

59:53.000 --> 01:00:00.000
I believe if all the good work that we did in Apollo, I think was important and I'm very proud of it.

01:00:00.000 --> 01:00:10.000
But I think perhaps one of the best things or accomplishments we had was to leave a legacy to carry on in much the same way.

01:00:10.000 --> 01:00:18.000
And when Jerry says the young people over in the control center today are a lot smarter basically than we are and we were.

01:00:18.000 --> 01:00:21.000
I'm not sure they're any better, but they're a lot smarter.

01:00:23.000 --> 01:00:25.000
They're a lot smarter and they got better tools.

01:00:26.000 --> 01:00:33.000
But I think the thing that is best about it is that they have retained that decision making capability.

01:00:33.000 --> 01:00:42.000
As far as I can tell, management at the higher levels have not penetrated into it with the micro management fingers.

01:00:42.000 --> 01:00:44.000
And I hope it stays that way.

01:00:44.000 --> 01:00:48.000
A lot of this had to do incidentally and reason I wanted to answer this for Gene did.

01:00:48.000 --> 01:00:51.000
Gene had a lot to do with this.

01:00:52.000 --> 01:00:54.000
Gene was all of our bosses.

01:00:54.000 --> 01:00:57.000
He started a trend.

01:00:57.000 --> 01:01:07.000
He and Chris Kraft working together in those years of the late 50s, early 60s, set a tone that has carried forward to today in mission operation.

01:01:07.000 --> 01:01:10.000
Now I say he was always the boss.

01:01:10.000 --> 01:01:14.000
I came back in 82 as the center director so I had him render me for a while.

01:01:14.000 --> 01:01:16.000
But I never did get control of him.

01:01:17.000 --> 01:01:21.000
I really about two or three very quick thoughts there.

01:01:21.000 --> 01:01:27.000
They talked about mission control and the motto they've got is Achievement through excellence.

01:01:27.000 --> 01:01:36.000
And I believe it's this excellence which has allowed the people today to be as good possibly even better than they were in the past.

01:01:36.000 --> 01:01:39.000
So really they've got a standard of excellence they've set.

01:01:40.000 --> 01:01:43.000
The expectations they say are set on themselves.

01:01:43.000 --> 01:01:47.000
Everybody up here understands the words we use discipline, morale, tough and competent.

01:01:47.000 --> 01:01:52.000
Those are what we must be ourselves and that is what we expect others to be.

01:01:52.000 --> 01:01:55.000
I think that is good and I think there's a legacy that's been passed on.

01:01:55.000 --> 01:01:59.000
We were very fortunate again to be brought up.

01:01:59.000 --> 01:02:03.000
Chris Kraft we used to call the teacher for a very straightforward reason.

01:02:04.000 --> 01:02:10.000
I remember the first day I ever stepped up to the flight director's job and he always had a hand over in there.

01:02:10.000 --> 01:02:13.000
And I said Chris where's your hand over and there wasn't one.

01:02:13.000 --> 01:02:15.000
He says what do you want me to do?

01:02:15.000 --> 01:02:17.000
He says he's head set away.

01:02:17.000 --> 01:02:22.000
He says you're the flight director and he walks off council.

01:02:22.000 --> 01:02:29.000
So I think there's that kind of a legacy from a standpoint of management that we really have to be careful.

01:02:29.000 --> 01:02:34.000
Because if we're to be successful in space flight because space flight doesn't take a lot of second guessing.

01:02:34.000 --> 01:02:36.000
And people got to respond very quickly.

01:02:36.000 --> 01:02:41.000
They have to be part of the game plan from the very beginning to the time they execute this thing.

01:02:41.000 --> 01:02:48.000
There is such thing as personal responsibility and accountability and that still must remain with the people.

01:02:48.000 --> 01:02:56.000
So if there's a message for the generation of managers we've got around here, you cannot corrupt the accountability and responsibility.

01:02:57.000 --> 01:03:00.000
It has to be in the hands of the people doing the job. That's it.

01:03:03.000 --> 01:03:05.000
Let's give them all a big hand.

01:03:12.000 --> 01:03:15.000
That concludes our program for this afternoon.

01:03:15.000 --> 01:03:20.000
The open house will be shutting down at four o'clock so the facilities will be closing.

01:03:20.000 --> 01:03:24.000
But we're glad to have had you here today. We hope you've seen the pride that we have and the work that we do.

01:03:24.000 --> 01:03:28.000
There will be the balloons lifting off at six o'clock out by rocket park. Thank you.

